# OpenMowerNext: Windows Simulation & Setup Guide

This guide is a comprehensive technical walkthrough for running the `OpenMowerNext` ROS 2 simulation stack on Windows via Docker Desktop and WSL2. It includes critical bug fixes, setup commands, and step-by-step instructions for using the Foxglove interface and Map Recorder.

---

## 🏗️ 1. Prerequisites & Environment

1. **Docker Desktop**: Ensure Docker Desktop is installed and configured to use the **WSL 2 backend**.
   * Open Docker Desktop `Settings` (the gear icon top right).
   * Go to `General` and ensure **"Use the WSL 2 based engine"** is checked.
   * Go to `Resources` -> `WSL integration` and ensure integration is enabled for your default WSL distro.
   * Click Apply & Restart.
2. **VS Code**: Install VS Code with the `Dev Containers` extension.
3. **Foxglove Studio**: Download the desktop app or use the web version (https://studio.foxglove.dev) to interface with the robot.

> [!WARNING]
> **WSL2 Clock Desync Bug (Windows Specific)**
> WSL2 frequently suffers from hardware clock drift when Windows goes to sleep. This causes the Docker `xserver` GUI container to crash on boot with `gettimeofday` looping errors.
> **The Fix:** Before starting Docker containers, open PowerShell and run:
> `wsl -d docker-desktop -u root hwclock -s`

---

## 🚀 2. Building and Launching the Simulator

Due to Github Container Registry (`ghcr.io`) authentication requirements on the pre-compiled images, it is highly recommended to build the Devcontainer locally.

1. Open a terminal in the root of the `OpenMowerNext` repository.
2. We must pass required environment variables into the container or the navigation stack will crash:
   ```bash
   # (For PowerShell, set these in your session first)
   $env:OM_MAP_PATH="/config/map.geojson"
   $env:OM_DATUM_LAT="51.5"
   $env:OM_DATUM_LONG="7.5"
   ```
3. **Build the image locally:**
   ```bash
   docker compose build workspace
   ```
4. **Boot the simulation:**
   ```bash
   docker compose up -d
   ```

> [!TIP]
> **Viewing the 3D World:** Once the containers are up, open a browser and go to `http://localhost:12345`. This connects to the VNC X-Server container showing the Gazebo interface. Note: The grass patch model is huge and may take a minute or two to download on the first run.

